# Low-Power ALU (Arithmetic Logic Unit) Design using Verilog

## Abstract

This project presents the design and verification of a Low-Power Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) using Verilog HDL. The ALU performs arithmetic, logical, shift, and comparison operations while incorporating low-power design techniques such as operand isolation, RTL clock-enable, and low-power mode control. Functional verification was performed using Icarus Verilog and GTKWave.

---

# 1. Introduction

An Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU) is a fundamental component of a processor responsible for performing arithmetic and logical operations.

Modern digital systems require low-power operation to reduce energy consumption, heat generation, and improve battery life. Therefore, low-power techniques were incorporated into the ALU design.

---

# 2. Objectives

* Design a parameterized ALU using Verilog HDL.
* Implement arithmetic and logical operations.
* Generate status flags.
* Apply low-power design concepts.
* Verify functionality using simulation and waveform analysis.

---

# 3. ALU Operations

| Opcode | Operation   |
| ------ | ----------- |
| 0000   | ADD         |
| 0001   | SUB         |
| 0010   | AND         |
| 0011   | OR          |
| 0100   | XOR         |
| 0101   | NOT         |
| 0110   | Shift Left  |
| 0111   | Shift Right |
| 1000   | Increment   |
| 1001   | Decrement   |
| 1010   | Compare     |

---

# 4. Low-Power Techniques Used

## 4.1 Operand Isolation

Inactive datapath blocks receive zero-valued inputs, reducing unnecessary switching activity.

## 4.2 RTL Clock Enable

Registers update only when the enable signal is active.

## 4.3 Low-Power Mode

Shift activity is reduced and arithmetic operations can be optimized for lower switching.

